# Coding Practices

General standards for all frontend code in this project.

## TypeScript

- Write all source in TypeScript — no plain JavaScript files.
- Type component props explicitly; export prop types when a component is shared.
- Avoid `any`; use `unknown` and narrow when the type is uncertain.
- Colocate types with the feature (`types.ts`) or next to the component when small.

## React

- Functional components only — no class components.
- One component per file; name the file after the component (`UserCard.tsx`).
- Keep components small and focused — if a file grows past ~150 lines, split it.
- Extract reusable logic into custom hooks (`useXxx.ts` in `hooks/`).
- Prefer composition over prop drilling; lift state only when multiple siblings need it.

## Reusable Components

Build a shared UI layer under `src/components/` — do not duplicate markup across pages.

| Layer | Location | Purpose |
|-------|----------|---------|
| UI primitives | `components/ui/` | Button, Input, Card, Badge, Modal — generic, no business logic |
| Shared | `components/` | App-wide pieces used across features (layout, nav, empty states) |
| Feature | `features/<name>/components/` | Components tied to one domain |

Rules:
- Pages compose shared and feature components — pages should not contain raw form markup or repeated Tailwind blocks.
- UI primitives accept `className` for extension; expose variants via props, not copy-paste.
- When the same JSX appears twice, extract a component.

## Project Structure

```
src/
  components/ui/     # reusable primitives
  components/        # shared app components
  features/          # domain modules (components, hooks, api)
  hooks/             # global custom hooks
  pages/             # route-level components (thin)
  lib/               # api client, utils, query keys
  routes/            # React Router config
```

Pages are thin: they wire data (React Query) and render feature components.

## Styling

- Use **Tailwind CSS** utility classes — see `design.mdc`.
- Brand tokens come from the graphic charter — see `graphic-chart.mdc`.
- No inline `style` except for dynamic values from data (e.g. institution color).

## API & Async State

Every data-driven view must handle all three states explicitly:

| State | Pattern |
|-------|---------|
| Loading | `<Loader />` from React Loader Spinner |
| Error | User-friendly message + retry when possible |
| Success | Render data; show empty state when the list is empty |

With React Query:

```tsx
const { data, isPending, isError, error, refetch } = useQuery({ ... })

if (isPending) return <Loader />
if (isError) return <ErrorMessage error={error} onRetry={refetch} />
if (!data?.length) return <EmptyState />
return <ItemList items={data} />
```

- Mutations: use `onSuccess` / `onError` with React Toastify — not `alert()`.
- Do not fetch with raw `useEffect` + `fetch` when React Query fits.

## Production-Ready Code

- Ship code safe to run in production — no debug UI, commented-out blocks, or dev-only shortcuts.
- Do not leave `console.log` for debugging.
- Handle errors explicitly; do not swallow failures silently.
